Bike Sharing User Perspective

Abstract

What does the user think about the bike sharing system they are using.

Transactions

The data provides records for each completed trip. We transform this data to transactions, here each transaction is either a bike rent or a bike return. Thus each trip will be converted into two transactions, one going out (rent) and one in (return).

The columns in the transactions are,

## [1] "statn_loc"  "user_id"    "trxn_type"  "bike_nr"    "time"      
## [6] "subsc_type" "birth_date" "gender"

The column statn_loc should provide the location of the bike-station, either directly as (long, lat) or as a label along with a dictionary that can be queried with that label. The hubway data has birth-dates and gender for the users, which we have included here, however we may not want to use this data if it will unavailable in our case-studies.

We can take a peek at the transactions in our sample week,

In some of our analysis we will need the data to be in the form of trips. We will need functions to make translate from transactions to trips, however for the moment we will just use hubway.sample data set for this purpose.

User features

In order to study the users, we extract features from their usage data. The features we will discuss are as follows, 1. Frequency of use 2. Duration of trips 3. Intermittency of use 4. The diversity of start stations 5. The diversity of end stations 6. The diversity of (start, end) station pairs.

To illustrate the features we will use the hubway_trans data with disambiguated user ids, as our starting data. We will need trips for some of our computations.

Frequency of use

A user’s frequency is the number of times they have used the bike-sharing system, or the number of trips they have made. We will assume that a user who rents a bike also returns it in the dataset.
